Anonymization¶

The dataset's features can be categorized into the following

Qualitative data: ID, Tweet URL, Group, Collector, Category, Topic, Keywords, Account handle, Account name, Account bio, Account type, Location, Tweet, Tweet Translated, Tweet Type, Content type, Reasoning, Remarks

Quantitative data: Timestamp, Joined, Following, Followers, Date posted, Likes, Replies, Retweets, Quote Tweets

Note that the crossed out features above are identifiable features. In order to anonymize the data, we have to remove these features.

In [20]:
dataset['Account code'] = pd.factorize(raw_dataset['Account handle'])[0]

identifiable_columns = ['Tweet URL', 'Account handle', 'Account name', 'Account bio', 'Tweet']
dataset.drop(columns=identifiable_columns, inplace=True)

Try making some code for quick-checking formats:

In [23]:
counts = 0
for date in dataset['Date posted']: #check formats of date
  is_wrong = False
  date_posted = date.strip().split()
  date_format = date_posted[0].split('/')
  time = date_posted[1].split(':')
  if (len(date_format) != 3 or len(time) != 2 or  #if formats are right they should have the right length
    int(date_format[0]) > 31 or #low level check of day
    int(date_format[1]) > 12 or #check month
    int(date_format[2]) > 22 or #check year upper bound
    int(date_format[2]) < 16 or #check year lower bound
    int(time[0]) > 24 or #check hour
    int(time[1]) > 59): #check minutes
      print(date)
      is_wrong = True 

  if is_wrong: counts += 1

print("Number of wrong formatted cells under Date posted column:", counts) 

counts = 0
for date in dataset['Joined']: #check formats of date
  is_wrong = False
  date_joined = date.strip().split('/')
  if (len(date_joined) != 2 or  #if formats are right they should have the right length
    int(date_joined[0]) > 12 or #low level check of month
    not(int(date_joined[1]))): #should return an error if year isn't a number
      print(date)
      is_wrong = True 

  if is_wrong: counts += 1

print("Number of wrong formatted cells under Joined column:", counts)

Number of wrong formatted cells under Date posted column: 0
Number of wrong formatted cells under Joined column: 0

Formatting of relevant columns looks correct.

Binned graphs¶

One idea is to bin the graphs by event. Because the event relevant to the study is Kian delos Santos's death, we can separate the times around the event (arbitrarily, from August 2017 to October 2017). There are two possible ways to bin the remaining tweets: either all in their own bin, or two separate bins (one before the event and one after).

Starting with the first (one bin for the event and one bin for otherwise):

In [28]:
event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] <= "2017-10") & (dataset['Month'] >= "2017-08")].shape[0] #number of tweets found within 08-2017 and 10-2018
non_event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] > "2017-10") | (dataset['Month'] < "2017-08")].shape[0]

d = {'Bin': ['From Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017', 'Outside Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017'], 'count': [event_bin, non_event_bin]}
small_dataset = pd.DataFrame(data=d).set_index('Bin')
small_dataset.plot.bar(width=1, edgecolor = 'black')

plt.xlabel('Bin')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.title('Histogram for Amount of Mis/Disinformation Tweets on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')

plt.xticks(rotation=6)

print("Total tweets:",event_bin + non_event_bin)

Total tweets: 60

Now the second (three bins: before, during, after):

In [29]:
event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] <= "2017-10") & (dataset['Month'] >= "2017-08")].shape[0] #number of tweets found within 08-2017 and 10-2017
after_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] > "2017-10")].shape[0]
before_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] < "2017-08")].shape[0]

d = {'Bin': ['Before Aug. 2017', 'From Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017', 'After Sept. 2017'], 'count': [before_bin, event_bin, after_bin]}
small_dataset = pd.DataFrame(data=d).set_index('Bin')
small_dataset.plot.bar(width=1, edgecolor = "black")

plt.xlabel('Bin')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.title('Histogram for Amount of Mis/Disinformation Tweets on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')

plt.xticks(rotation=10)

print("Total tweets:", event_bin + after_bin + before_bin)

Total tweets: 60

The above binned graphs have bins of unequal time ranges (that is, the event bin is 2 months long while every other bin is much longer), thus further into the project clustering may be used to bin the timeframes instead. The above graphs serve more as quick tests.

Finding the number of unique accounts¶

Thanks to the new "Account code" column, we can easily count the number of unique accounts:

In [30]:
print("Number of unique accounts:", dataset['Account code'].nunique())

Finding accounts with multiple tweets¶

Through pandas' indexing system, accounts with multiple tweets are easily found.

In [31]:
print("Displaying account codes which appear more than once:")
account_codes = dataset['Account code'].value_counts().index[dataset['Account code'].value_counts() > 1].tolist()
account_counts = dataset['Account code'].value_counts()[dataset['Account code'].value_counts() > 1].tolist()
for code, count in zip(account_codes, account_counts):
  print("Account code:", code, "| Count:", count)

Account code: 5 | Count: 3

Average number of tweets per account¶

A fun statistic to find may be the average number of tweets per account:

In [32]:
print("Mean number of tweets per account:", dataset['Account code'].value_counts().mean())
print("Median number of tweets per account:", dataset['Account code'].value_counts().median())

Mean number of tweets per account: 1.1764705882352942
Median number of tweets per account: 1.0

It appears that the mean amount of tweets an account has in the dataset is approximately 1.17, though the majority of the accounts in the dataset are unique. Note that only 5 accounts appear in the dataset more than once.
